		<div class="title">
			<h4><a rel="nofollow" id="comment_link_65283369" name="comment_link_65283369" href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23656629&amp;cid=65283369" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(65283369)" >Is it copying their work though?</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_65283369" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 65283369); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>3</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~Talon0ne">Talon0ne</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~Talon0ne">( 10115958 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_65283369">		
		on Saturday April 05, 2025 @10:51AM (<span class="ind"></span><a rel="nofollow" href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23656629&amp;cid=65283369">#65283369</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_65283369"><p>It seems to me like AI is just sort of 'ingesting' content, internalizing it, and building its world view based on it... Just like a person would.  No word for word copying is going on (otherwise the model would be many many terabytes)... So IMHO this should be dismissed, plain and simple.</p></div>
	</div>

