</li><li id="tree_65283747" class="comment full contain"><span class="ind"></span>
<div id="comment_status_65283747" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_65283747" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_65283747" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a rel="nofollow" id="comment_link_65283747" name="comment_link_65283747" href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23656629&amp;cid=65283747" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(65283747)" >Fair Use Takes a Hit in NYT v. OpenAI</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_65283747" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 65283747); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>3</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~rocket+rancher">rocket rancher</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~rocket+rancher">( 447670 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_65283747">		 &lt;<a href="mailto:themovingfinger%40gmail.com">themovingfinger@gmail.com</a>&gt;
		on Saturday April 05, 2025 @03:37PM (<span class="ind"></span><a rel="nofollow" href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23656629&amp;cid=65283747">#65283747</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_65283747"><p>I just plowed through the full 47-page ruling in New York Times v. OpenAI, and the Ars Technica summary leaves out some of the most important bits.</p><p>Yes, the judge let key claims move forward&mdash;including contributory infringement&mdash;but Ars barely mentions the most striking part: the court rejected OpenAI&rsquo;s &ldquo;substantial noninfringing use&rdquo; defense, calling it a &ldquo;straw man.&rdquo; The judge made clear that ChatGPT&rsquo;s ongoing relationship with users means OpenAI could still be liable if its models regurgitate copyrighted material. This is a big deal. It shows courts may not treat LLMs like neutral tools&mdash;and that alone could reshape how AI output liability works.</p><p>Also missing: while the NYT&rsquo;s &ldquo;hot news&rdquo; and DMCA claims were tossed, similar DMCA claims from other plaintiffs in the consolidated cases survived. That nuance matters. As a co-defendant in this case, Microsoft got out clean this time, but the ruling invites a deeper discussion on whether Big Tech partners are merely embedding AI&mdash;or helping build bullet-proof copyright infringement engines.</p><p>This ruling is a canary in the coal mine for Meta and others. If courts follow this logic, arguments about &ldquo;fair use&rdquo; and &ldquo;general-purpose tools&rdquo; may not be enough to avoid discovery&mdash;or liability. The AI legal landscape just got a lot more real.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_65283747">
